  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n- Provides guidelines for financial institutions and governments\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigating financial crimes\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Provides standards for banks to prevent money laundering\n- Promotes best practices in financial transparency\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Sets regulations for member states\n- Requires financial institutions to conduct customer due diligence\n\n5. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Supports countries in developing anti-money laundering frameworks\n- Provides technical assistance and policy recommendations\n\nThese laws and regulations require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting requirements\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Share information across borders\n- Impose penalties for non-compliance\n\nMost developed countries have domestic laws that align with these international standards.",
